Q1 First principles: wrong representation of adversarial gateways - evidence: nodes 1, 3, 7, and 10 all improved fixed B_dev but failed the high-Sybil held-out case, while node 9 cut Sybil but lost delivery.  
Q2 Hidden assumption: a neighbor’s risk can be estimated from local edge/peer outcome counters alone - if dropped, topology around the next hop can act as a structural prior before sparse feedback arrives.  
Q3 Elephant: trunk has no explicit notion of “this neighbor is a bridge into a suspicious cluster,” so early packets can train on damaging Sybil contacts.  
Q4 Hamming: yes; the repeated dev/test split says static and feedback-only penalties are saturated, so a cheap structural prior is worth one cycle.
